data.name: label12.Text
data.value: Pia mater or vascular meninges is a conjunctivo-vascular membrane, with a nutritional role, that wraps the marrow to which it adheres intimately, penetrating into ditches and cracks. In its thickness are found numerous arterial vessels and nerves, especially sympathetic. The pial prolongations penetrate, together with the arterial branches, into the nerve substance, participating in the formation of the blood-brain barrier.

data.name: label11.Text
data.value: The outer membrane is called dura mater. It has a fibrous, resilient lamellar structure and is separated from the walls of the vertebral canal through the epidural space where connective and fatty tissue is located, as well as multiple anastomoted veins. The upper, at the level of the occipital hole, continues with the cranial duramater. The lower ends in the bottom of the bag, in which are housed terminal filum and horsetail. Below the S2 vertebra, the terminal filum, along with the dural shell with which it comes in contact, forms the coccygeal ligament. Arachnoid has a connective structure and is separated from the dura mater by the subdural mater space through the subarachnoid space, which contains the cerebrospinal fluid (CSF).

data.name: label1.Text
data.value: It consists of three protective membranes that wrap the marrow. At the occipital hole the spinal meninges continue with the cerebral meninges.
